sentences: Olav Basoski (born 1968, Haarlem, Netherlands) is a Dutch DJ, remixer, house music producer and trainer in Electronic dance music techniques.
He is best known for records such as "Windows" (1991), "Don't turn your back on me" (1993), "Opium Scumbagz" (2000) and "Waterman" (2005).

In the mid-80s, he was listening to the radio at night and heard a disco record, when suddenly he realised he was listening to a different record, this was his first experience of mixing records.
One day he sent in a selfmade mixtape to Ferry Maat's radioshow the Soulshow.
Ferry was so enthusiastic about his mix, that from that moment on Ferry Maat started the Bond van Doorstarters (a weekly 15 minute mix item in the Soulshow).
In 1988 he made his first production, together with Sander Hoeke, under the name of Baze & Hucke with "Pitbull Terror".
He was successful for the first time in 1991.
In 1993 "Don't Turn Your Back On Me" became a popular release of this project.
In 1997 he started the "Samplitude" series.
This series of EP's had a large amount of releases, especially between 1997 and 2002.
In 1998 he collaborated only once, with Armin van Buuren as Wodka Wasters, with "Pass The Bottle".
In the summer of 2000 he made his breakthrough in the UK with "Opium Scumbagz".

In 2005, Basoski teamed up with the British dancehall artist Michie One to record "Waterman".
, it became a hit in the United States at both clubs and radio, where it debuted at number 22 on Billboard's Hot Dance Airplay chart in its March 27, 2006 issue.
Basoski has had two hits in the UK Singles Chart, "Waterman" (#45, 2005) and "Opium Scumbagz" (#56, 2000).
